### Outbound HTTP Connection Reuse

Every outbound HTTP(S) request Node.js makes goes through an `http.Agent`, which is responsible for managing the underlying TCP connections — including whether to reuse an existing connection (keep-alive) or open a new one per request. Opening a new TCP connection means a full handshake (and, for HTTPS, a TLS handshake on top) before a single byte of the actual request is sent — for services making many requests to the same downstream host, that handshake overhead repeated on every call adds real latency.

The default global `http.Agent` actually has `keepAlive: false` historically (changed in some contexts, but worth verifying for your Node.js version) and a connection limit that can become a bottleneck: with `maxSockets` capped, requests beyond the limit queue up waiting for a free socket rather than failing or opening more connections, which under high concurrent load to one host silently serializes requests that should be running in parallel.

```typescript
import https from 'https';
import axios from 'axios';

// Explicit keep-alive agent: reuses TCP+TLS connections across requests
const agent = new https.Agent({
  keepAlive: true,
  keepAliveMsecs: 30_000,    // how long an idle socket stays in the pool
  maxSockets: 50,            // max concurrent connections per host
  maxFreeSockets: 10,        // idle connections kept ready for reuse
});

const client = axios.create({
  httpsAgent: agent,
  timeout: 5000,
});

// Every request through this client reuses pooled connections instead of
// renegotiating a fresh TCP+TLS handshake each time
const { data } = await client.get('https://api.example.com/users');
```

For modern Node.js, `undici` (the HTTP client now powering the built-in `fetch`) handles connection pooling more efficiently by default than the legacy `http`/`https` modules, with HTTP/1.1 pipelining-aware pooling and a simpler configuration surface — worth considering directly for services making heavy outbound HTTP traffic rather than configuring `http.Agent` by hand.

**Common pitfall:** instantiating a new `Agent` (or a new HTTP client instance with its own default agent) per request instead of reusing one configured agent across the application's lifetime. Each fresh `Agent` starts with an empty connection pool, defeating the entire purpose of keep-alive — the connection-reuse benefit only materializes when the *same* agent instance is shared across many requests to the same host, not recreated each time.

