### diagnostics_channel: Patterns for Library Authors and APM Integration

Well-designed channels follow a naming convention: `<package>:<component>:<event>` (e.g., `undici:request:create`, `mongodb:commandStarted`). This enables targeted subscriptions and wildcard-based APM instrumentation.

Node.js 18+ exposes built-in channels for the HTTP client (undici), which `fetch` uses internally, and `net`. Subscribing to these channels enables zero-modification HTTP tracing.

```typescript
import { channel, subscribe, unsubscribe, Channel } from 'diagnostics_channel';

// Pattern: library publishes to multiple lifecycle channels
const channels = {
  start: channel('mylib:http:request-start'),
  end:   channel('mylib:http:request-end'),
  error: channel('mylib:http:request-error'),
};

async function httpRequest(url: string, options: RequestInit) {
  const requestData = { url, method: options.method ?? 'GET', startTime: Date.now() };

  if (channels.start.hasSubscribers) channels.start.publish(requestData);
  try {
    const response = await fetch(url, options);
    if (channels.end.hasSubscribers) {
      channels.end.publish({ ...requestData, statusCode: response.status, duration: Date.now() - requestData.startTime });
    }
    return response;
  } catch (err) {
    if (channels.error.hasSubscribers) {
      channels.error.publish({ ...requestData, error: err, duration: Date.now() - requestData.startTime });
    }
    throw err;
  }
}

// APM subscriber — collect all HTTP metrics
subscribe('mylib:http:request-end', ({ url, statusCode, duration }) => {
  metrics.histogram('http.client.duration', duration, { url, statusCode });
});

// Unsubscribe cleanup (important in tests)
const handler = (data) => console.log(data);
subscribe('mylib:http:request-start', handler);
// later:
unsubscribe('mylib:http:request-start', handler);
```

**Common interview trap:** Using a single channel for all events and embedding event type in the payload. This forces every subscriber to filter events, increasing CPU usage even for irrelevant events. Separate channels per event type mean subscribers only pay for what they actually need. Also: `subscribe()` returns an `AbortController`-compatible unsubscribe handle in Node.js 18.7+ — use it to avoid holding references to subscriber functions in tests.

